# Coding Style Rules

## Variable Naming Convention
- Use PascalCase for all variable names with a single lowercase letter prefix indicating the variable type
- Type prefixes:
  - `n` - Numbers (integers, floats): `$nCount`, `$nTotalPrice`
  - `s` - Strings: `$sFirstName`, `$sErrorMessage`
  - `b` - Booleans: `$bIsValid`, `$bHasPermission`
  - `l` - Lists and Arrays: `@lStudentList`, `@lPrimeNumbers`
  - `d` - Hashes (dictionaries): `%dConfigOptions`, `%dUserPreferences`

## Examples
```perl
# Good - Type prefix + PascalCase
my $sUserName = "John";
my $nAge = 30;
my $bIsActive = 1;
my @lNumberList = (1, 2, 3);
my %dPersonData = (Name => "Alice", Age => 30);

# Avoid - No prefix or wrong naming style
my $user_name = "John";
my $userName = "John";
my $UserName = "John";
my @numbers = (1, 2, 3);
```

## Subroutine Parameters and Local Variables
- Apply the same naming convention to all variables including:
  - Subroutine parameters
  - Local/lexical variables (my)
  - Loop variables
